  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT208-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">varaiviṭai “āṟṟal vēṇṭum” eṉṟa tōḻikkuk kiḻatti uraittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the confidante, who said “one has to have
          the strength to [await] the time of separation”. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT208">
        <lg type="edition">

          <l>oṉṟē ṉallē ṉoṉṟuveṉ kuṉṟattup</l>
          <l>porukaḷiṟu mititta neritāḷ vēṅkai</l>
          <l>kuṟavar makaḷir kūntaṟ peymmār</l>
          <l>niṉṟukoya malaru nāṭaṉō</l>
          <l>ṭoṉṟēṉ ṟōḻi yoṉṟa ṉāṉē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

          <l>Not that I am not one; I am one</l>
          <l rend="indent">-because of one thing <note place="foot">How to understand the statements
            in lines 1 and 5 and their relation to one another? Is line 1 meant generally, while
            line 5 names the special occasion of HER not being content with HIM? In any case oṉṟu
            remains mysterious, and Cām.'s explanations that either a stranger has come to marry her
            or that he has failed to come to the appointed meeting, are pure speculation. And the
            kiḷavi does not even venture to give a solution.</note> , friend, I am not one</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with the man from the land, where the Vēṅkai flowers,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">to be plucked while standing <note place="foot">What is expressed by <term xml:lang="ta">niṉṟu? </term> That even the women can now reach the branches now that
            the tree is crushed?</note> ,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">for the women of the hill people to wear in [their] tresses,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[its] crushed trunk trampled by the fighting elephant bulls</l>
          <l rend="indent9">of the hills.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
